representing the impulse \(\vec{R}_p = R\hat{\theta}\), and
\(\hat{\theta}\) represents a unit vector in the direction of increasing
spherical coordinate \(\theta\).

Next, with the incident state known, we split the impulse vector into
perpendicular and parallel components with respect to the plane that
is tangent to the cone at \(P\), of the cone, various cases for the
exit velocities of a billiard. Those cases by first considering two
